meta {
  name: GET /api/facts/:patientId — full fact bundle
  type: http
  seq: 3
}

get {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/api/facts/margaret-chen
  body: none
  auth: none
}

assert {
  res.status: eq 200
  res.body.patient.id: eq margaret-chen
  res.body.facts.length: gte 1
  res.body.documents.length: gte 1
}

docs {
  # Full fact bundle — the citation substrate

  **What it proves:** the complete stored record the LLM features are
  grounded in. Every fact carries provenance (`source_document_id`,
  `sources`), and `documents` contains the **full source documents** —
  this is what the panel's Sources tab and citation deep-links render
  from, and what chat citations (verbatim `cited_text` spans) verify against.

  **Response shape** — `200`, the raw `FactBundle`:

  ```json
  {
    "patient": { "id", "openemr_patient_id", "name", "demographics" },
    "facts": [
      {
        "id": "fact-mc-med-001",
        "fact_type": "medication",
        "content": { ... },
        "is_current": true,
        "laterality": null,
        "verification": "...",
        "source_document_id": "...",
        "sources": [ ... ],
        "created_date": "...",
        "updated_date": "..."
      }
    ],
    "contradictions": [ ... ],
    "images": [ ... ],
    "treatments": [ ... ],
    "documents": [ ...full text, not just metadata... ]
  }
  ```

  **Why it matters for grading:** take any citation from a chat `done`
  event (its `document_id` + `cited_text`) and find that exact span inside
  the matching `documents[]` entry here — the citation chain from LLM
  output back to a verifiable stored source document closes on this
  endpoint. Brief items likewise carry fact/citation refs that resolve
  under `facts[].id`.

  **Failure modes:** `404 {"error":"patient_not_found"}`;
  `503 {"error":"store_not_configured"}`.
}
